LOCALITY: Dajibanpeth Dajiban Peth Road, Hubballi, Karnataka, IN (15.347, 75.14)
TRIP COMMENTS: With pavan miskin and kishore panaghanti
SPECIES COMMENTS: Female individual of Lesser Florican was spotted on 17th of November, in the evening hours of old Hubballi . Mr Pavan Miskin, our resident bird rescuer, recieved a phone call informing him of a largish bird found in exhausted condition behind City Clinic, Dajibenpet, Hubli, Karnataka. Mr. Pavan Miskin rescued the bird, with inputs from Shri Niranjan Santh, it was identified as a female lesser florican. Inputs and guidance were obtained by NKBN from S/Shri Samad Kottur, T V Manjunath, CCF, Vijay Mohan Raj, CCF, Niranjan Sant and Saleem Hameed. On the next day (18th Nov) the bird was released at the outskirts of Hubli. The primary concern was for its early release due to its agitated behaviour as dawn passed. The species was never recorded earlier in or around the region. This highlights the need for immediate resurvey of the bird population in the area for better understanding of the status and behaviour of this species, related species of its family for chalking out better conservation strategies.

TRIP COMMENTS: Tiger

with Rita, Dan Singer, Steve Bailey. Two 3-hour game drives, one 6:30-9:30, and the other 3-6 p.m. We have local guides (Dennis today) and drivers in the park. Two tigers -- male & female -- seen today [we also did a game drive yesterday afternoon and saw a different male and different female]; photos of all.

Locations covered include Ranthambore National Park (Jeep safari), Soorwal Lake, Sawai Mansingh Sanctuary and the Chambal River.  An effort was made to cover as many sites as possible in the limited time that we had. 125 species in 9 hours was an excellent result, considering the fact that it was the end of the dry season and only breeding species were present in the area.

Five 2-hour trips into Ranthambore park Feb 23-25th.  Did a jeep trip to Sector 4 on AM of 23rd (two tigers) and back to same tiger kill on PM of 23rd in Cantor. Did Cantor trip to same tiger kill area in Sector 4 again (tiger out of sight) on AM of 24th and jeep trip to Sector 6 in PM.  On 25th one more Cantor trip to Sector 4 but drove around as no tiger.  Only the jeep trips really offered chance at bird sightings.

Followed the trail in the forest from entrance to the foot path from the water tank

Covered three of the six grassland areas in this round. The grasslands on either side of the road in the approach to the lake and the one on the right side on the road to Hudduth beyond the lake. The trip was primarily intended to look for grassbirds. The sky was overcast and light poor, not great for Photography but great for counting bristled grassbird. The habitat is primarily tall grass which is wet from the rain. There is not much water on the ground except for patches of swampy areas in between, There are some Prosopis juliflora schrubs, some of which dry and leafless and some occassional tall grasses in between.--Later on when we checked areas with shorter grass, there were no bristled grass birds. It is preferring areas with tall, newly grown grass. --

--Main grassland, along the road at the edge of grssland, into the grassland and back. On the agenda were looking for the Indian eagle owl that prefers this spot. We were discussing striated grassbird which was on top of the agenda but were not expecting it since it was already a bit late. But the sky was overcast and gloomy, and light low. As soon as I said look for a bird that looks like zitting cisticola but is much bigger, Nishith spotted the bird sitting on a dry bush without leaves. We took pictures it flew away and and when we were about to leave we spotted the bird sitting another hundred yards away.. Then we managed to record the sound and also take more pictures. Then it circled the whole grassland area includng the grassland adjacent to the forest. The photo of the habitat is given below. I was thinking it was bristled grassbird and same birds but on processing I realized that the two were different birds due to variations in plumage. On posting in Indian birds it was the consensus that it was bristled grassbird. Matching the call and other features confirmed it. --

Forest, forest-grassland edge and the nearby residential areas.

Started birding the SGPGI grassland area and continued into the forest area. so both grass and woodland species in the list. One Indian eagle owl was sighted on a tree in the middle of grassland and later a pair of eagle owls were sighted in the forest area (they were also sitting facing the grassland at the other side of the campus). Are there one or two pairs of eagle owls? The other highlight was the jungle prinia in the middle of the forest.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Minimum of two but possibly more. Sighted three birds at two different sites. First one on one side of the campus and then two at the other end. The first one is a regular at the perch where we see it regularly and the other forms  a pair. was the first one a part of the second pair.

Name of species: Indian eagle owl--Date of death: 25.03.2015--Time: Sometime in the night hours--Cause: electrocution--Place: Alangiam Village, Dharapuram, Tirupur District--Co-ordination: 10.669x77.502--Narration: On my morning birdwalk in this area I found numerous crows are flying over an electrical post mid of agrifield for feeding something.. when I reached close found this eagle owl electrocuted. Should have tried to perch on this electrical post for watching a prey existence in the area and should have got in contact of two poles of electric current.. Immediately reported to forest personal and they have recovered the carcass for atopsy... ----Time approximate. Submitted by S. Kalidass

TRIP COMMENTS: A birding trip was undertaken along the Pothundi-Nelliyampathy Road on the morning of 19th April 2019. The primary purpose was to explore the patch of forest adjacent to the check-dam near Kaikatty where Nilgiri Thrush had been recorded one week back. However, birding on the ghat road was quite abundant and so the birding party stayed back at various points on the Pothundi - Kaikatty Road and did birding.--Initially, the weather was cloudy and misty as it had rained extensively on the previous evening. However, the sun became bright and hot as the day progressed. --On earlier occasions, the road traffic and tourist traffic was very minimal, as had been the case after the floods. But, on this occasion a large number of vehicles were seen going to the higher reaches of the hills.--The birding party consisted of 3 persons: Mr. Namassivayan L, Ms. Apitha Namassivayan and Mr. Venugopalan R.

Next to it was a huge pile of garbage and unfortunately the green munias were seen feeding on the ground littered with trash.Not sure what they were feeding on the ground where the garbage was thrown but we saw them climb the rocks where some millets were thrown for sparrows and the munias were seen feeding on the millet.

IN-West Bengal-Barria-Ajodhya Hills Road - 23.215x86.114 - 9 Nov 2017 6:22 am
TRIP COMMENTS: Ajodhya Hills is a hill located in the Purulia district of the state West Bengal, India. It is a part of the Dalma Hills and extended part of Eastern Ghats range. Highest peak of Ajodhya Hills is Gorgaburu(855m). The nearby populated town area is Bagmundi.This is the watershed between Kasai and Subarnarekha rivers.The main land-use is agriculture but a large part of the total forest area provides fuel wood for the population residing in the area. The large wetlands like the Loharia Dam are used as fishing by the fishermen of the area.This dam was washed away during monsoon of the year 1999.It was reconstructed thereafter. Suchitra Ghosh and her team conducted a survey on the Biodiversity of Ajodhya Hill in 1999 and details report was published in Naturalist journal in 2004- a report by Santanu Manna----mail : birdwatcherssocietyofbengal@gmail.com

TRIP COMMENTS: A birding trip was undertaken along the Ghat Section of Nelliyampathy Hills on the 23rd of September 2017 (Saturday). LOCALITY: The Hill, Dhanori, Pune, Maharashtra, IN (18.614, 73.913)
TRIP COMMENTS: A hot sunny day. Real feel of 36 Deg at 9:00 am when actual temp 23 deg
SPECIES COMMENTS: It was a chance meeting. I was descending the North Eastern side of The Hill, which is also dense with vegetation and many tree species, I heard a call which was very eerie and mysterious. It wasn't bird like and definitely not the distinct woo-hooo that REO makes. I tried recording it with my phone but upon checking later, it turned out to be a failure. The sound was animal like, and for a few seconds I had decided against investigating it, especially as the day had turned out to be very hot and I had lot of distance to cover. However, I decided to move towards the call and it gave away my position to the bird which decided to fly away and that's when I realized my good fortune. From its low flight, I knew that REO would have relocated nearby... and then we found each other. I was lucky to spot its perch timely, else REO would have definitely flown away this time.

LOCALITY: Taklang La pass, on Leh to Manali road, Ladakh
TRIP COMMENTS: While on a birding trip to Eastern Ladakh to Changthang, with couple my friends, we stopped at the popular Bearded Vulture Nesting site at Taklang la pass (5329 m) on Leh Manali Highway. We scanned the slopes of the rocky face where Lammergeire nests for few years on. Accidentally we came across a pair of Saker Falcon, on enjoying a kill (most probably a pigeon) and other hopping around and often entering the Bearded Vulture nesting site! These two photo (though blur and not good quality) shows their presence and breeding possibility in and around Tsokar and Taklang La pass which was recorded by some birders earlier.
SPECIES COMMENTS: On birding trip to Tsokar, we stopped at the site to check for any sight of Bearded Vulture and we were surprised by presence of these pair of Saker Falcon.

TRIP COMMENTS: Where searching for Green Avadavats in Oriya Village. Some boys (age 8-11) knew about green munias as many bird watchers come seeking for this species. The boys kept insisting that we should come tomorrow at 7 am as this was not the ideal time to see the munias. A few young boys were eager to show but probably didn't say much because of the older boys. We still decided to go further inside the village and search. We showed pictures to some local men and women but they did not have a clue. When we had given up and thinking of coming back the next day at 7 when suddenly a girl age 10 called Manisha came and saw the picture that I was showing her mother. She volunteered to come with us and show us the spot where the munias are often seen. We followed her and her friend Santosh (age 7). We tried few places and at one place we saw a bird which looked like green munia but before we could have a good look it flew away. After much searching Manisha was able to show us a spot which after scanning revealed two green munias foraging on rocks. They then flew down on a grass bed and continued foraging.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Seen foraging on the  boulders. Probably feeding on tiny invertebrates on rocks as we found many of tiny insects on the rocks that we were sitting. They then landed on the ground covered with 2 inches of grass. Record shot and videos taken. Habitat shot taken- Fallow land with grass growing (~ 2 inch thick, huge rocks and boulders around)

Venuchettan and myself. On a trip to Mookunnimala on the old Yezdi bike. Climbed up the hill from the Military firing range.
SPECIES COMMENTS: The bird was spotted at a distance of 100 ft, sitting open on a big boulder. the habitat was perfect for this species with lot of rocks strewn all over the hill top among the tall grass. The bird appeared very large with the upright ear tufts and the brown body. The orange eye could be seen through the old Ross 7 x 50 binocular (Raghuchettan's). The bird sat on the rock for more than 5 minutes before disappearing on the southern side of the hill.

TRIP COMMENTS: Birding
Birding

With Apith.  We have been hearing the calls of the Great Hornbill from the northern mountain parts, but today they were heard from inside our regular haunt.  Tough I attempted recording their continuous call, later it is found that the micro SD card is having some contact problem and lost the recordings .   Thereafter at the fag end of the observation period it was made correct but the Great Hornbills had left their perch . There was good bird activity and full of calls.  A nesting hoopoe
SPECIES COMMENTS: calls, first from the northern mountain part then from inside our regular observation area and the southern hill slope bordering the area.  For about 20 minutes intermittend calls.  Though I recorded the calls and when checked later it was found that nothing is recorded and the micro SD card is facing some contact problem.  Thus lost their calls.--Post Script: 24-04-18: subsequently the files are recovered. Now editing done with high amplification and some cutting, for the purpose of record it is uploaded here

A birding trip was undertaken to the Chenathu Nair Reserve Forest at the extreme North-Western corner of the Malampuzha Reservoir.  Over the years a high level of bird density has been recorded at these forests.   During the last floods in August 2018,  this area has suffered very extensively.  Large scale tree falls,  soil erosion,  appearance of sand banks where none existed earlier etc are some of the developments.  A large number of trees have toppled over opening up the canopy in many places.--The weather was overcast in the morning and the sun had not risen.--The birding party consisted of 2 persons:  Mr.  Vivek Sudhakaran and Mr.  Venugopalan.  R.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Call heard from a nearby location.  The birds could not be seen.  But on earlier occasions,  the birds have been photographed from this area.

On BBD with Sureshji and team
Submitted from eBird Android 1.0.2
Observations done by Suresh Sharma and Jagat Varma --BBD2014-DL-11
Bhindawas Lake Bird Sanctuary was birded by me and my team of 18 members in all.

I birded here with Peter Kennedy; our birding guide was Sanjay Sharma, our driver Sohan Singh.Temperature was 38 degrees Celsius. Before birding the loop road around --the sanctuary, we also birded along a good-sized canal nearby.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Sanjay said that this was a Eurasian Eagle Owl, but my photos show that --this was an Indian Eagle Owl, now known as the Rock Eagle Owl, Bubo --bengalensis. Several checkists on eBird from this site show Rock Eagle --Owls here, but none show Eurasian Eagle Owls. My photos and video show --a bird with dark borders to the facial disk; most of the plumage details do --differ from those shown on Plate 92 in the new edition of Grimmett and --Inskipp, but on the whole, the bird looked way more like the Rock Eagle Owl --than the Eurasian. Sanjay found this bird by quietly walking ahead of Peter --and me, then walking back past us, checking trees along the canal. --Eventually, it flew along the canal right past us, then up into a tree, where it --perched for quite a while, affording us very good views through my scope.

This was the last day of 4 day trip to Athirapally. We planned to go up to Valparai, if time permitted. However, as our main focus was birding, we only went up to Upper Sholayar Dam and returned back. It was once again a fruitful day. Apart from many bird species, we could also see Lion Tailed Macaques. We started early by 6.30am from the guest house, stopped at the Church Point (where we saw Lion Tailed Macaques), spent sometime on the Tribal Village Road and also at Tribal Village, and longer time on a Forest Trail leading to a Tribal Colony in Idamalayar Reserve Forest. We stopped near a Tea Estate for lunch and then proceeded up to Sholayar Dam, before started returning.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Seen and photographed by a member of the team, while many of us taking Forest Trail in Idamalayar Reserve Forest. However we saw them flying and heard the noise made by their wings while flying.

TRIP COMMENTS: This is a comprehensive list of recorded sightings for July 2012 @ Thol.

Peter Kennedy and I birded here with the guide Sanjay Sharma. Our driver --was Sohan Singh. Sanjay told us that this birding area was "discovered" --by one Peter Jackson, whose name I reckon is one by which to be --reckoned. We drove out 0.5 kilometers, and covered some ground on foot, --for about 1.0 kilometers, then drove over to the north section of this site, --where we covered another 2.0 kilometers or so, from 0910-0940. At one point --we headed south on a long, straight, paved dike, with a river to our left. --Sanjay said that this site is in Gurgaon. ----Totals for "Drain Number 8" area, then, would be 2.5 kilometers, 0720-0940, --two hours and twenty minutes, party of three birders (not counting the driver --Sohan, of course).----In my notes, I wrote "Nefghar Lake," but I see on eBird that it can be called --Najafghar Jheel.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Small terns with orange bills, blackish bellies, grey upperparts, black crown, --and "swallow-tails."

TRIP COMMENTS: This is the Nemmara Forest Division south-east boundary which is on the wat to Kuriyarkutty from Nelliyampathy.  This was a pre independence leased estate by the State of Cochin and resumed after the lease period.  Mainly coffee plantation wherein big trees and fig trees are left in tact.  This also forms a buffer area for the Parambikulam Tiger Reserve.  There is a 10 acre pond near the I B wherein there is full of water throughout the year and is a general attraction for the elephants and carnivore in the night, apart from the many deers. Birders 1. Gopal Prasad, 2. Apitha and L.Namassivayan. There is a fruiting fig near to the pond mentioned above.  Sunny, cool breeze.  The said fig is full of green pigeons and there were 23 Great Hornbills on it and and on a neighbouring tree
SPECIES COMMENTS: on the big fig tree and on a large big tree.  Takes to wing simultaneously and comes back after 15-20 minutes.  Sometimes noisy too.  Photos and calls taken

A birding trip was undertaken to the Nelliyampathy Hills in Palakkad district early in the morning on 27th April 2019, Saturday. The main aim of the trip was to record the Great Hornbills and for this purpose the birding party repeatedly went to Victoria Estate. While these birds could be seen from a distance no good photograph could be obtained. --On the way up the hill, the birding party tarried at various strategic points and did birding. --The birding party consisted of 3 persons: Mr. Namassivayan L, Ms. Apitha Namassivayan and Mr. Venugopalan. R.--The weather was hot and humid. Even though it was expected that the hills would experience the after effects of cyclone Fani, there was no cyclone at all.--One of the highlights of the trip was the dead sambar in the compound of the Oriental Estate.
SPECIES COMMENTS: 2 Hornbills were seen flying away.  While the birds could be seen clearly,  they could not be photographed.

Traveling by S.T.bus from Solapur to Akkalkot.
SPECIES COMMENTS: While traveling by bus,from Solapur to Akkalkot,our journey was obstructed by a herd of cattle which was crossing the road.The bus obviously slowed down. Suddenly a bird took off from fallow field on the left and rose into the sky.I immediately realized that this was a different bird that I had never seen before.Within moments it flashed through my mind that this was  female lesser florican.The bird then flew across the road over our heads (slow-moving bus) and landed on the other side of the road in another fallow field at about 100 m. away.As the bird flew across the road from left to right,we also shifted our positions (seats) from left to right,the bus being quite empty.For few minutes we could watch the bird very clearly ,till the  the bus regained its speed.We were so exited that we shouted loudly in joy and attracted passengers' attention. The spot was few kilometers before Valsang. This is,so far,the first and the last sighting of lesser florican for me.My colleague/co-passenger here,was Mr.Prakash Purandare from Pune.

SPECIES COMMENTS: The Bird was sitting on a tree & self and Manish were doing birding behind Academic Staff College ,JNU .Thejus was suppose to join us but he got delayed .Suddenly my phone started ringing and Thejus was on the line and asked me about our current orientation in that grassland.The moment I turned my head it flew from a dead tree branch just behind me after hearing my voice call and flew away but not far and settled on the college building. By the time we all reached there it was chased by crows and it returned to the same area .Which 3 of us couldn't locate. All of a sudden Thejus called me that SP turn back it is right behind you. His voice was little loud and it got disturbed once again and flew . We tried to relocate but in vain. We all had a wonderful sighting of the same.

https://archive.org/details/NLBW4/page/n71----The United States Information Service, Trivandrum, held a semi- --nar on American Literature at Thckkady on the 1st and 2nd of --April 1964Â» I had the good fortune to be one of the invitees. --As far as birdwatching is concerned, I was not so fortunate --for the time available for outings was very limited. Still, I --managed to snatch a few minutes every now and then and go about --the immediate neighbourhood of the Aranya Nivas and Edappalayam --Tourist Bungalows where, by turns, we had -our meetings.. Almost --all the birds listed here will, therefore, be found to be those --occurring in places within easy reach of the casual visitor. ----Of the two Tourist Bungalows , the one at Edappalayam is much --less attractive to the birdwatcher. The Aranya Nivas Bungalow --and the II Class Tourist Bungalow close by are just ideal. The --whole area is full of large trees and, judging by the surpris- --ing number of very large nests on these trees, should be most --interesting during the period (November, December, January ?) --when the large birds of prey breed there. Many of the trees - --carry boards which give their botanical, vulgar, and local names, too. ----Most of the birds listed are those seen during three hours spent --wandering about between Aranya Nivas and the II Class Tourist --bungalow on 3rd April. ----I have no surprises in store-, for those who have watched birds --in Thekkady. Of the 135 or so birds which Dr. Salin Ali records --Â£see 'The Ornithology of Travancore and Cochin', J. Bombay nat. --Hist. Soc. 37(4) through 39(3)7 for the area, I saw (and, irTH" --Tew instances, only heard!) 62. Some of the shier birds did not --venture to enter the bungalow grounds; most of the migrants --wore absent or so rare that they were missed. ----The only 'exciting' experience of the trip was the discovery of --a roost of the Grey Wagtail ( Mot a cilia caspica ) at Edappalayam --about which I have sent a note to- the Journal of the Bombay nat. --Hist. Society.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Date of death: 25.03.2015--Time: Sometime in the night hours--Cause: electrocution--On my morning birdwalk in this area I found numerous crows are flying over an electrical post mid of agrifield for feeding something.. when I reached close found this eagle owl electrocuted. Should have tried to perch on this electrical post for watching a prey existence in the area and should have got in contact of two poles of electric current.. Immediately reported to forest personal and they have recovered the carcass for atopsy...

SPECIES COMMENTS: Large sized, heavy, brownish bird. Got flushed when we were searching for Quails. Flew away from us at 90degree and we could notice only the body structure and the Bustard like flight with heavy wings and protruding neck. Settled in about 1.5ft tall grass about 40m away. On approaching, it took a longer flight, again at 90deg away from us and landed in 3 to 4ft tall  fresh grass about 200m away. Could not locate it after this. First Id without any thought was of McQueen' s Bustard, but after size comparisons  in field guides, habitat and season, we concluded the id as Lesser Florican female.

LOCALITY: Mudumalai National Park--Wilds at Northern Hay Resort
TRIP COMMENTS: Walked trails around Wilds at Northern Hay Coffee Estate in Singara Checkpost area of Masinagudi. This is contiguous with the Mudumalai Tiger Reserve. We were guided by a local birder. Rich in bird species.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One of the best sightings. The bird is a resident and came every day to a ficus tree just 10 feet behind the main cottage of the Wilds to feed on the fruit. Spent 60 minutes watching it at close range without the need of a binoculars. Perched on a branch, the bird stretches and contorts itself to delicately pluck off the fruit. Given the size of the bird and its beak, its mastery of balance and precision is magical.

I am very pleased to be working in association with BNHS in the activity of Bird Count. I am happy to share my little count in this big event. Avian diversity of Washim district must be registered with the record of BNHS on 15th November, 2015. To my surprise I have observed tremendous bird activities around my house after uploading of my morning observations. I bird known as Jacobin jacobe is sighted and it gave me further encouragement in bird count. I decided to go at site rich for birding, 12 KM away from Washim i. e. Ekburjee Dam. This dam is a man made water reservoir and breeding and feeding ground of many resident and migratory birds. Today I went there for bird count. Here, I am delighted to add the extended list of birds counted today at water reservoir of Ekburjee/Washim. I am very proud to mention the name of my better half Advocate Lalita as she accompanied me and encouraged to complete the task to contribute information with BNHS.

Paul Pandian invited me to visit the sanctuary to count and census the birds one early February morning.  Travelled from Tiruneveli by local bus.  The journey takes 1 to 2 hours depending on local language and art of reading routes.   The bus takes you safely by road to Moolakaripatti and take a cab or auto to Sanctuary.  Recorded close to 50 species .  The Bar headed Geese were the highlight of this trip. The Eagle owl was breeding nearby in an abandoned quarry.

Hoskotte Lake or Kerre in Kanada is an ancient catchment area draining water from nearby rain run offs.   Also used for irrigation.   The lake water levels are higher post monsoon and in summer vast boundaries are exposed to encroachers and farmers who practice vegetable farming.    The lake has a variety of seasonal, endemic and migratory birds finding a secure space for close to 4 months to 6 months .    Fishing too is a practice here.   The ecosystem looks sustainable but needs a boundary marker.

TRIP COMMENTS: with Gopal Prasad, Sulaiman Karimpara, Sivadas Chettur and Apitha. Trekked from Victoria to Alaxandria estate route. The fig trees all around are in fruition. Great Hornbills were found in them. We were on our way to stay at Thoothampara Foresst Bungalow, Cloudy and misty, pretty cool also here.
SPECIES COMMENTS: almost all the figs on the road side from Victoria to Alaxandria are bearing ripe fruits.  Many of the figs are of the species Strangular Fig.  The Great Hornbills are there all over the figs; but they appeared to be scary and took to flight even when we were very silently approaching.  We got a sing male alone on a tree at the tri-junction on the road to Alaxandria where there is a dilapidated small building and a branch road takes you to the Pakuthippalam estatenroute.  He appeared to be cool, forafing in a low height fig, silent, and flew just over the ground through a valley to a tall tree.

TRIP COMMENTS: Pleasant morning, hot sun, clear skies.  21:48-49. BSAP outing. Water level quite low. Lots of ground exposed in front of barrage where 3 Mugger crocodiles were basking. The boats had to be dragged & punted almost up to the pumping house in mid-barrage before the outboard motor could be started. Mallesh, the APFD forest guard claimed a population of 10,000 painted storks on the island. But I have my doubts. A maximum of 1,500-2,000 birds might exist on this island though we counted around 500-600 individuals. Over 35 head of cattle were seen grazing on the islands from the bund. Erythrina indica is flowering near the EC.

With Prashant, Kandarp and Vivek. Scops owl was a pleasant surprise in addition to the striolated bunting and a yet to be identified Bush Robin. Around dusk a hyena pair and two half grown cubs were an unforgettable experience.  Saw them for around 30 minutes and one adult followed us back to the car in the dark to ensure that we departed. Very surprising gave a yelping growl twice within 20 metres of us, to scare us to call reinforcements? Blue rock thrush roosting in a hole in a rock seen and photographed in the dark by torchlight after viewing the hyenas was another memorable sighting.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Heard after dusk. Noticeable lack of calls and sightings for Chamardi.

Biswamoy Biswas was born on 2nd June 1923, son of a professor of Geology.Biswas was a brilliant student and gold msdalist at his graduation.He was an indefatigable worker,often staying in the museum far into the night after everyone else had gone home. The results were numerous clarification in our understanding in Indian genera of birds. Biswas obtained his Ph.D from the university of Calcutta (1952) and took charge of the Bird and Mammal section of the Zoological Survey of India (ZSI). Later until retirement in 1981,he was joint Directorof the ZSI and the Emeritus scientist until 1986.Having adopted a modern genus concept ,Biswas published in 1953, A Check-list of Genera of Indian birds,the basis of all future taxonomic papers for the subcontinent. Of greater importance,he wrote the fundamental 12-parts The Birds of Nepal (1960-1967) and jointly with Salim Ali and S. Dillon Ripley, The Birds of Bhutan (1995). A born naturalist and conservationist,Biswas was spent as much time as possible in the field. He helped to establish the Salt Lakes and Narendrapur wildlife santuaries near Calcutta. He was a member from 1958 of the International Ornithological Congresses. The Asiatic Society awarded him the Joy Govinda Law Memorial Medallion in 1975. A new genus of flying squirrel, Biswamoyopterus biswasi is named in his honour. Numerous students obtained their Ph.D under his supervision. A life long bachelor with a retiring, almost shy personality he was. He lived frugally and donated most of his saving to charity.With the death in Calcutta of Biswamoy Biswas was on 10 Aug 1994,India lost its foremost bird taxonomist and we lost a great teacher. Here I am sharing his specimen collection from East Calcutta wetland and it is my tribute to this great man.- by Santanu Manna(info collected from net)----    IT IS SPECIMEN COLLECTION REPORT OF DR BISWAMOY BISWAS--    (report collected from Fauna of West Bengal by ZSI)--    Information collected from 'A guide to Birds of Salt Lake,Calcutta and change detection study' published in March 1999----    mail : birdwatcherssocietyofbengal@gmail.com

TRIP COMMENTS: Was leading a birding / photography tour from 20th to 23rd Jan'16 to Tal Chappar WLS and Bikaner (Jorbeed) .....Started the trip from Jaipur and closed in Bikaner. Most accompanying participants were photographers with few regular birders. Have been doing this circuit since Many years now (5 years) and pretty much know certain spots to get the target species. However it was very very cold and the Spiny-tailed Lizards (one of the main sources of food for raptors) were hibernating, so the overall raptor population was very less. With almost no sightings of Laggar in Chappar and no signs of White-eyed Buzzards, which are otherwise abundant during this time. We did see large congregation of Eagles and Vultures in Bikaner and a fantastic sighting of the Rare Saker Falcon. Would be visiting these places again in Feb'16.----Before breakfast searched the salt pan area for Stolickza's Bushchat..... this area is a good place to get this species, however the Prosopis plants have invaded this place and are rapidly taking away the habitat..... Dipped on the Stolickza's Bushchat (White-browed Bushchat), but got other species. ----Accompanying Birders: --Mandar Khadilkar, Sejal Jani, Leonard Rebello, Vinit Rau, KV Subbu, Mayur Shinde + 5 others
SPECIES COMMENTS: On their regular roost (abandoned well).....1 pair with a chick.....there were presumebly 2 chicks, but we got just 1

SPECIES COMMENTS: Observed clearly one male Lesser Florican in breeding plumage. He was making its signature jump in the Moong cultivation, by making a frog like noise. Hen+ size, white collar, whitish wing coverts. Long legs (folded during the jump) and curved backward long neck while jumping. Black head, neck and underparts, also observed the ribbon like 3-4 feathers arose from bird's ear area.--Recorded and photographed.

Siruvani; Pattiyar bungalow, birding around for half an hour and then walked 2 km on the way to Kerala Medu and returned when Dr Rajesh Radhakrishnan and his son Skandapoorvaja joined us. Cool weather initiall, but throughout breeze; very less water at the main parts of the Reservoir and in front of the Pattiyar very very less or no water, especially towards east. Yesterday night almost full moon.  We had the idea of searching for the presence of Great eared nightjar, but yesterday night around Pattiar and some time in the dusk at the Reservoir roads did not yield it.--No hornbills seen except the calls of the Great Hornbill from the forests opposite to the IB--No crows in and around Pattiyar IB--Woodpeckers very less, except for 2 or 4 numbers no ther species seen--Gopal Prasad saw a Malay Night Heron (Tiger Bittern) under the bridge, 1 km on the road to Kerala medu, but it flew off before giving us a picture; though we entered the stream and searched for it for some time, could not come across it.  Many times we went to the spot again and again but could not find it again; and hence not included in the list--the Forest Wagtail is conspicuous by its absence--Team: Gopal Prasad, Apitha and L.Namassivayan
SPECIES COMMENTS: calls being heard from the opposite side forests of the Pattiyar..monosyllabic calls

A  birding trip was undertaken to the Left Ring Road at Malampuzha on the evening of 15th November 2016.  The purpose of the trip was to record the Rock Eagle Owls  which are known to occur in the hill-side adjoining the Ring road.  While the own was heard calling from a distance,  due to disturbance on account of road traffic, good recordings could not be made.--The weather was bright and sunny to begin with and the sun set around 6 PM.  --The birding party consisted of Mr.  Namassivayan L,  Mr.  Lijo George and Mr.  Venugopalan R.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Previous record from this location.  The bird was heard calling from the hill-side adjoining the Left ring road.

TRIP COMMENTS: A birding trip was undertaken across the South Ring Road in Malampuzha with the primary aim of recording the Jungle Nightjar which had been recorded in this location earlier.  During the trip Indian Nightjar was active and slightly vocal, the other nightjars could not be traced.  The birding party consisted of 2 persons:  Mr.  Namassivayan L and Mr.  Venugopalan R.  The weather was sunny and bright.  A portion of the meadows in the reservoir bed was covered by the birding trip which explains the presence of meadow  and water front birds.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One bird was heard calling from a distance and an audio record of its calls has been captured.

TRIP COMMENTS: A birding trip was undertaken to Malampuzha (Left Ring Road) during the evening of 24th November 2016. As opposed to the normal practice,  this spot was approached from the Elivaal side.  The main purpose of the trip was to try to record "Bubo Bengalensis" which is known to occur at this area.  The bird did call repeatedly,  but the calls were not loud enough and the casual tourists around this spot were making too much of back-ground noise.  This disturbance made audio recording impossible.  --The birding party consisted of Mr.  Namassivayan L and Mr.  Venugopalan R
SPECIES COMMENTS: This bird is known from the location.  Earlier audio records of the calls exist.  On this occasion also audio records were made,  though of poor quality.

SPECIES COMMENTS: WE went to nelliyampathy to see the mejestic beauty from 7am we were --searching... enquired to many but they told this is not the time ,and we can se some flying hear and there occationally,,we were about to leave,,just enquired to some local people workeres in the coffeee plantations they told to go in a route,,, on the way asked to many workers they told they heard a call.. we waited and got a call..then another one told go forwerd you can see more..and when we was about to turn a curve road... saw them...1 2 3 4 5 ......we stopped the car......adn thenm came a bullet and it blowned the horn and that was it more than 50 started flying from 2trees...first time seeing this much... we waited few hours then slowley they started to comeback....meanwhile got a leopard pugmark also from that area--These ware one 2 trees... At first we saw 2 and then started counting more.. counted 19 then a bullet came and blow horn and then it was 50 plus from that and the nearby tree.only when it flew i saw it from other trees also .managed to count 51 and 52 me and my brotherinlaw we both counted seperately... --Latter we waited and when they came back managed to clik photos--They ware feeding.. these trees was full of small fig like fruits ... Trees was inside a coffee  plantation big trees.. hardly 80 to 100 meter from road.. easily visible from road... Nearby landmark is the s curve road before colany.--A very small stream is there after the trees.

TRIP COMMENTS: Early in the morning on 30th May 2019, a birding trip was undertaken to different spots along Ghat Road connecting Pothundy to Nelliyampathy. The birding party reached the first spot by 6.20 AM.   This checklist represents the birds seen in and around Thampuran Kunnu near the viewing deck on the Ghat Road.--At Thanpuran Kunnu,  on the road side,  there were a number of trees which bore goose-berry sized berries.  It was observed that a large number of fruit eating birds were flocking to these trees for feeding.--The weather was misty and overcast and the sun had not come out so early in the morning.--The birding party consisted of 2 persons: Mr. Vivek Sudhakaran and Mr. Venugopalan. R.

A birding trip was undertaken along the Victoria -Pakuthippalam road on 23rd September 2017 (Saturday) to try to record the Great Hornbills usually seen in this area.--The weather was hot and sunny.--The birding party consisted of 3 persons:  Mr.  Namassivayan L,  Ms.  Apitha Namassivayan and Mr.  Venugopalan R,--On a  disused estate route branching off  from the Victorial Pakuthippalam road,  the hornbills could be heard on a tree very near the road.  Subsequently,  we saw 8 great hornbills flying away,  even though photographs could not be obtained.  The birds were very noisy making all kinds of very loud noises.  Some good quality audio recordings could be obtained.
SPECIES COMMENTS: On the road to Pakuthipalam fro Victoria,  a disused road branches off to an estate taken over  by the Government.   On this road,  very near the road side,  hornbills were heard making a big racket.  Subsequently,  two batches of hornbills,  each consisting of 4 birds, were clearly seen flying away.  As the birds were flying from the tree top,  they could be clearly seen and the 'woosh'  sound of the wings also could be hear.  Quality audio recordings have also been obtained.

LOCALITY: Nelliyampathy, Upper deck view point near Ayyappan temple
TRIP COMMENTS: After what was a very busy birding day in Nelliyampathy and surroundings we were returning to Palakkad, rather disappointed at not being able to get a good look at the great hornbills. We stopped at the first view point, near the Ayyappan temple, on the way down to take in the breathtaking landscape. Without warning, two great hornbills flew into the valley below us. All of us were caught unawares, and did not have the camera on hand!  The party included Adv. Namassivayan Lakshmanan, Apitha Namassivayan, Gopal Prasad and Dr. Rajesh Radhakrishnan

TRIP COMMENTS: Drove for a dawn breakfast at a shrubby field and looked at some small birds and then went out to Bustard spot and then drove to headquarters to pay.  Sat there for about 30 minutes and then headed off to Mandvi for lunch and beach
SPECIES COMMENTS: Went to a known spot beside a large solar electric facility that had just been built (habitat loss?). Veer, Yvette and I walked down the dead end road and at the end looking out over the field we saw 3 birds. They were a bit distant but good light and got the scope on them and watched them for some time as they disappeared and reappeared from behind shrubs and grasses. They flew over to the next field just as we were going to leave so saw them in flight as well. Overall a good sighting and rather lucky as they are not always seen without huge effort. Less than 200 left.

The first bird i saw came from east, caught a fish and flew again towards east, carrying the fish. Black belly and orange bills were prominent. Again i saw 2 birds flying individually towards east at different instances. Not sure if they were the same bird i saw first or different individuals. Attaching cropped and uncropped images.

@7:29 am. An adult bird in breeding plumage was picking its prey from water surface and started flying high towards east.----@7:36 am: An adult in breeding plumage was flying low over water towards east.----@8:10 am: 2 adults in breeding plumage were seen. Soon they started to play chasing each other. In the middle, another adult tern in breeding plumage passed by and headed towards east. The couple's play lasted more than 15 minutes, then i missed tracking them.----For the first time i'm seeing more than 1 BB-Terns at a time.

By boat off Nirma Plant with Uday, Kandarp and two others. Went up the Gulf of Cambay northeast for about three kilometers. Went out with the high tide and got thousands of shorebirds along the coast. Later with the ebb tide grounded ourselves on a mud bank and spent almost 6 hours in the sun till the evening high tide brought us in. The flats above with thousands of mud skippers and a few crabs. Lunch was freshly caught prawn masala and rice. The catch also included a 4 ft long seasnake.

SPECIES COMMENTS: On 18th Nov, Bibiblal found a bird which was fallen down due to electric shock from electric line. Later with the help of people like Unnikrishnan, Jaffer Pallot, Sathyan Mepayur, Mujeeb Rahman they identified the bird as Lesser Florican. The bird was taken to a vet and was treated. Also Bibinlal informed the Forest Department about the incident. Later it was decided to keep the bird with Bibinlal who has good experience in taking care of birds. ----On 12th Dec, after checking with the Vet and the forest department, it was decided to release the bird around 25 kms from the place where the bird was found. The bird was released on a grassland area.  The bird flew to the grassland and we tried to located it after and was not successful in locating it again.----Forest Department Personnel were present when the bird was released. Also the whole process is well documented.

TRIP COMMENTS: Went to release the Lesser Florican to its natural habitat.The injured bird was found and rescued by Bibinlal.--Accompanied by Dr.Jafer Palot,Amrita Pakrashi,Charesh,Lata prabhakaran,Jamaludheen Karivelil,Shajahan and Renju T R
SPECIES COMMENTS: The species is highly endangered. The bird was found injured and rescued by Bibinlal.It was released in to its natural habitat in Ponkunnu Hill,Kakkur,Calicut,Kerala

SPECIES COMMENTS: The bird was seen flying over the car from one side of the road to the other after the right turn towards the dirt track for Mohit Farms. The habitat was rocky cliffs on both sides and the bird was seen clearly for 4-5 seconds before it vanished. Body structure and overall appearance indicated a Rock Eagle-Owl,  which was the field ID. No other similar species are present in the region with which the ID can be confused. On further discussion in an online forum, the ID was confirmed by senior birders. The pictures are highly cropped frames extracted from a video shot on a phone. Pictures by my father: Rajesh Thareja

Was leading a birding / photography tour from 20th to 23rd Jan'16 to Tal Chappar WLS and Bikaner (Jorbeed) .....Started the trip from Jaipur and closed in Bikaner. Most accompanying participants were photographers with few regular birders. Have been doing this circuit since Many years now (5 years) and pretty much know certain spots to get the target species. However it was very very cold and the Spiny-tailed Lizards (one of the main sources of food for raptors) were hibernating, so the overall raptor population was very less. With almost no sightings of Laggar in Chappar and no signs of White-eyed Buzzards, which are otherwise abundant during this time. We did see large congregation of Eagles and Vultures in Bikaner and a fantastic sighting of the Rare Saker Falcon. Would be visiting these places again in Feb'16.----We were late to reach Jorbeed Carcass Dumping grounds, however the raptors were still active and got Great sightings of Saker Falcon, Yellow-eyed Pigeons and Common Starlings----Accompanying Birders: --Mandar Khadilkar, Sejal Jani, Leonard Rebello, Vinit Rau, KV Subbu, Mayur Shinde + 5 others

SPECIES COMMENTS: Smaller than River Tern (the only other tern we saw on the trip) but much blacker underneath than Whiskered Tern; flying around over the wetland but 'scope needed as fairly distant; bill colour not really discernable but looked pale, not dark. Only other confusable species is White-winged Black Tern which we initially thought they were, but black colouration was confined to the underparts, not the underwing coverts, and the birds had a black cap rather than whole head black.

SPECIES COMMENTS: 07:04 Nest on large Calophyllum austro-indicum tree. Tree diameter nearly 1 m, height 25-30 m, nest height at 14-15 m on main bole (where bole tilts away and a knob is formed). Vertical slit. We watch from far/safe distance hidden.--07:16 Chick heard, soft peeuw, peeuw calls repeated many times per min--07:47 Bird heard flying in, c. 7:50 perches near nest, scans around, preens, sits quietly over 20 min--08:10 male flies to nest and starts feeding c. 25 or 26 fruits, dropped one (elliptical fruits 1-2 cm long). Female takes fruit, chick heard as well. Male leaves at 08:24--08:34 A bird (prob. male) returns to near nest we leave. --08:42 from even further away we watch as male returns to nest and feeds several dozen fruits as chick cheeps. Fed 1 fruit every 2 s for 8 minutes at least.

TRIP COMMENTS: C.M Inglis was born 8 November 1870 in Elgin, Scotland, the son of Archibald Inglis, a retired planter in India. He  was a naturalist and curator of the Darjeeling museum in India from 1926 to 1948. The museum was run by the Bengal Natural History Society and many of his writings were published in that society's journal which he started and edited.While hunting in Bihar in 1935, Inglis shot the last specimen of pink-headed duck ever to be documented. The species is now presumed to be extinct. Inglis did not know what he had killed, until his dog, a retriever, brought the bird to him. He breathed his last in 1954. It is my tribute to a great naturalist - submitted by Santanu Manna----mail : birdwatcherssocietyofbengal@gmail.com

This checklist is an extract from Salim AliÅ› Birds of Mysore survey published in 5 part series in Journal of Bombay Natural History Society (1942 & 1944 JBNHS Vol.43 and 44) during his survey of erstwhile Mysore state (present Karnataka) between November 1939 to March 1940. An effort has been made to compile his notes/observations/specimen collected in these entries to ebird for easy access to any one who is searching for the information on this hotspot or species. Where the dates have not been specified its entered during one of these dates (basically to avoid a single species entry on ebird checklist) as he appears to have spent more time at Namadachilume and Devarayanadurga on these dates although his itinerary says he camped 31 December 1939 to 4 January 1940.----Current English and taxanomic names has been used in this checklist.

TRIP COMMENTS: We stayed in Jaisalmer, setting out at 0530 with guide Musa Khan, took tickets from Sudasari forest chowki, and drove through various areas until about 11am when we stopped for lunch at a nearby resort, and slept until 3.30pm when we set out again. I am not sure of the exact route but we saw a variety of different desert flora in different areas. There had been 1 good rain and 2 minor showers so far this monsoon. Bui and grasses (where grazing permitted) were shooting, kheemp was in flower, as were everywhere kair trees  with rosy starlings feasting on the fruit. There were strong winds all day with the roads becoming invisible under sheets of rippled sand. We also saw a desert cat (no sign of hybridity with all correct markings, long limbs) in hunting mode, and several small groups of chinkara, very many spiny tailed lizards, 8 or 9 nilgae, snf two desert foxes (separately) .
SPECIES COMMENTS: about 5.30 pm, we saw this adult male and stopped, staying in the jeep and making no sound.  He stood for some mnutes  and then very slowly walked away, pecking at morsels of food as he went.

This is a report based on photographs I took while holidaying at Valparai, near Coimbature, Tamilnadu betwen 26-31 December 2009. Our party consisted of T R Shankar Raman, Divya Muddappa, Mahesh Rangarajan, Uttara Rangarajan and myself for most of the journeys taken in and around Valparai, the tea estates and the rainforest around. We also saw the endangered Lion-tailed Macaques, Bonnet and Rhesus Macaques, Black Langur, Flying squirrels, Malabar Giant Squirrel, Striped Jungle Squirrel, Barking Deer, Gaur and abandoned tea/ coffee plantations reforested with the local rainforest species providing ample cover for birds and animals.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Heard and saw several in extremely low light.

SPECIES COMMENTS: We are going to the main stream of river ganges through the reeds from oxbow lake & observed 2 adult individual of Finn's Weaver, presently known as Yellow Weaver perching on reeds. The birds are completely adult & has complete yellow body. I was stunned to see them in this area. I asked the boatman about it & he said that he had seen the birds before in this area. Probably a nesting site to me, but I don't have any proof to establish my claim. But I never see this species there after that day on same location.

Birders :: Dipu K, Praveen J, Sachin Shurpali, Vinay Das--Weather :: Cloudy in morning and sunny later, rained after--3:00 PM--Remarks :: Not much birding till Kanakpura. After--Kanakpura, stopped occasionally and birded on the sides of the road (mainly--scrub and rocky habitats). Birded on the river bank at Srirangapatna while--eating our late lunch!----Highlights: It was fun to track a pair of Jungle Bush Quails though their--calls and finally manage to see them for a few seconds! At the same area,--also got nice views of a pair of Sirkeer Malkoha on the rocks. Another--interesting bird in the day was a nightjar (possibly Indian) which always--manage to hide from us and only gave us few flight views when flushed. 15+--Egyptian Vultures were soaring in the same area. Jungle Prinias were the--most common Prinia, singing all around. And towards the end, we had lunch in--the company of some nice birds like Common Kingfisher, Common Sandpiper,--Darter, White-breasted Waterhen etc.--https://groups.yahoo.com/neo/groups/bngbirds/conversations/messages/18760--Only Bannur checklist added here. Srirangapatana and Kanakapura checklist to be done separately

Drove a short distance from our lodge - Satpura Jungle Retreat - to a deep canal constructed in 1973 where an Eagle Owl roosts.  The other side of the canal is the buffer zone for Satpura NP.  We lucked out in seeing a magnificent male tiger.

TRIP COMMENTS: A birding trip was undertaken along the Ghat Road from Pothundy to Nelliyampathy, early in the morning on 26th May 2019. While the final destination of the trip was Victoria, on the way the birding party paused at various spots which appeared to be promising and birded around these areas.--The weather was bright, sunny, humid and hot. --The birding party consisted of 3 persons: Mr. Namassivayan L, Mr. Vivek Sudhakaran and Mr. Venugopalan R.

A  birding trip was undertaken to the Nelliyampathy Hills on 23rd September 2017 with the main aim of locating and photographing the Great Hornbills.  The birding party reached the Nelliyampathy Hills at 7 AM.  The weather was bright, sunny and hot.--The biding party consisted of 3 persons:  Mr.  Namassivayan L,  Ms.  Apitha Namassivayan and Mr.  Venugopalan R.--The Great Hornbills were seen to be very active,  moving around quite a bit.  One interesting factor was that the hornbills could be heard even at the beginning of the Ghat Road.

Parameswaran, Chetankumar Joshi and the heros Gajamohanraj & Kishorekumaran. While the Isabelline Wheatear was elusive, many of the usual suspects of the area were seen. SPECIES COMMENTS: In area around a tree in fruit on which they are feeding.  The tree is next to the pond that is near the wildlife observation tower.  While I was viewing them from the trail (behind bushes) one bird flew low toward me and started to perch 25 ft from me before at the last minute seeing me and flying off. Iâ€™ve seen a lot of spectacular birds in my life but this is by far the most spectacular.  (A flight of Roseate Spoonbills in sunlight is 2nd best; a flock of Rainbow Lorikeets 3rd best). Saw two birds land together and one bird feed the other.  Heard the "kok" call but not the duetting growl (but not by the feeding pair).

We had two Great Hornbill seen in flight and the record of Malabar Pied Hornbill I am guessing was of birds observed in the canopy. --Diagnostic characteristics for this species being the Black top to the cask. Smaller size than the Great Hornbill and separation in flight by the black band in the tail of the Great Hornbill along with white wing bars which are absent in the Malabar Pied Hornbill.----We had managed to see and photograph this species at Molem a week or so earlier so I was very familiar with identifying them

SPECIES COMMENTS: See, https://groups.yahoo.com/neo/groups/bngbirds/conversations/messages/11112----...... Before daybreak next day, we set-out with packed breakfast towards what is known as `Bottomâ€™, the bottom most spot along the banks of flowing Kali river to look for large hornbills â€“ the Great Pied and the Malabar Pied. Before we trekked down to the river-edge we halted little close to the Karnataka Power Corporationâ€™s (KPC) `Bottom Checkpostâ€™. The guards after confirming who we were and our purpose, slowly reveled with certain casual discard, that the hornbills regularly visited a fruiting Ficus infectoria (?), growing close-by. We positioned ourselves at a road-bend to look-up towards the tall canopy of the ficus growing some 20m away on a ridge, to wait for these large avian wonders. It was nearly half hour before the dawn broke to the distant cackling sounds of hornbills. As the day broke, we spotted two specks immediately below the `Sykeâ€™s Pointâ€™, a ridge that towered some 200m above us and a vantage point that provides a panoramic view of the dense forest clad steep-slopes of Kali river valley. The specks, what initially looked like a pair of Jungle crows soon transformed into Malabar Pied Hornbills, that came whiffling down in a rapid descent â€“ tumbling, as if they have been shot by bullets, and rolling both their wings side-ways, without a beat, in an effort to loose height rapidly and landed on the ficus tree in a matter of 3-4 seconds. As if on cue, other Malabar Pieds which appeared to have been waiting in all earnest on trees around the ficus, but at a safe distance, flew-in ones-and-twos towards the tree and in a matter of 10 minutes there were nearly 25 Malabar Pieds which had seized the Ficus canopy in a feeding frenzy, gobbling-up ficus berries one after another in quick succession. As the surroundings brightened-up cheers broke out amongst us, as there were five Great Pied Hornbills, which too appeared to be in a similar feeding frenzy. Sharing this feeding festivity in the Ficus canopy were the langurs and Malabar Giant Squirr--els. These large hornbills were soon joined by their much smaller cousins, the Malabar Grey Hornbills. As the hornbills bruised themselves in feeding on ficus, not bothered in the least by the occasional KPC traffic, it provided us some of the most memorable sights of their unique forms. When some of these birds took a break from feeding and perched on tree-tops in an ever brightening morning, we had fantastic views that left us with breathless wonderment â€“ and it truly looked like once-in-a life-time opportunity of seeing these large, unbelievably beautiful birds, that too, in such unusually large numbers.   .......

SPECIES COMMENTS: They were missing from the main quarry (because of the rock climbing gang & the noise they were making I believe) and also not in the 2nd rock face in south-eastern side. Luckily 2 of them were resting in the last rock face in the south-west end. One more flew by and landed in the thicket.

TRIP COMMENTS: BBD2014-TN-07--with: Sivakumar H / Chandrasekar S / Venkataramani M / Vijay KY / Bhanumathi
SPECIES COMMENTS: Resident & breeding in this quarry. About 3 of them are present all through out the year.

TRIP COMMENTS: Raptor Watch - field walk
SPECIES COMMENTS: Counts are within range for this location. As many as 7 individuals reside in this quarry.
